{
  "text": "In mammals, adiponectin (ADP), visfatin (Visf ) and chemerin (Chem) are adipokines produced and secreted by white adipose tissue. They regulate glucose and energy metabolism [CITATION_1] as well as reproduction including gonad steroidogenesis [CITATION_2] and gonadotropin secretion [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Adiponectin, one of the most studied adipokines, circulates in the form of homo-multimers [CITATION_5] and its impact is mainly via binding to the AdipoR1 and AdipoR2 receptors [CITATION_6] . Chem, or RARRES2, is a new adipokine that is involved in the regulation of adipogenesis, energy metabolism, and inflammation [CITATION_7] . Chemokine-like receptor 1 (CMKLR1), also called ChemR23, GPR1 (G protein-coupled receptor 1) and chemokine (C-C motif) receptor-like 2 (CCRL2) are G-protein-coupled receptors known to bind Chem [CITATION_8] . Visf is both a systemic adipokine and the cytosolic enzyme, nicotinamide phosphoribosyl transferase (Nampt) that is involved in metabolic (obesity, type II diabetes) and immune disorders [CITATION_9] . In constrat to ADP and Chem, no Visf receptor has yet been identified.",
  "correct_citation": {
